\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 01 DEDICATION\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [whispered, almost private]\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [kicker: \u8961? A book for slow readers]\i0\cf0\par
    For the ones who are tired of being fast. For my father, who carried his work in a tea flask and never once asked the world to look at him. For my mother, who taught me that watching is its own labour.\par
\par
\cf3\i     [kicker: \u8212? Non \u183? Shanghai \u183? Bangkok \u183? Boston]\i0\cf0\par
\par
\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 02 CONTENTS\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [section id: contents]\i0\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [matter-of-fact, almost a librarian]\i0\cf0\par
\par
    Contents\par
\par
    \u8226? I. Slow a defence of the unhurried p. 008\par
    \u8226? II. See attention as the only luxury p. 026\par
    \u8226? III. Less subtraction as a discipline p. 044\par
    \u8226? IV. Alone solitude as instrument p. 062\par
    \u8226? V. Time rivers, repetitions, a body that ages p. 080\par
    \u8226? VI. Make the dignity of small daily work p. 098\par
    \u8226? VII. Fail the tunnel that turns out to be a path p. 116\par
    \u8226? VIII. People the only mirror that matters p. 134\par
    \u8226? IX. Home three cities, two parents, one body p. 152\par
    \u8226? X. End the small word that holds all the others p. 170\par
    A note on reading. This book has no plot. Each spread is the size of a quiet thought. You can read it forwards on a Sunday, backwards on a Tuesday, or open a page at random for thirty seconds before bed. The art is half the book; the captions are the other half. Whichever you read first is correct.\par
\par
\par
\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 03 FOREWORD\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [conversational, like reading to a friend across a table]\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [kicker: \u8961? How this book wants to be read]\i0\cf0\par
    The book that is slower than you are.\par
\par
    I started this book because I was tired. Not the kind of tired you fix with a holiday. The kind you fix by remembering that watching a kettle boil is, in fact, a complete activity.\par
\par
    For most of my life I tried to be fast. I went to MIT to study architecture. I went to Harvard to study anthropology. I lived in Shanghai for ten years. I missed three deadlines, broke two relationships, and drank a great deal of coffee. The world, as far as I could tell, rewarded speed. So I gave it speed.\par
\par
    And then, very slowly, I noticed the things I was missing.\par
\par
    I noticed that the most interesting people I knew did not speak first. I noticed that the best architects I had read about \u8212? Louis Kahn, Tadao Ando, Geoffrey Bawa \u8212? were the ones who had waited the longest before drawing the first line. I noticed that my father, who never socialised and carried his lunch in a tea flask, was the calmest person in any room.\par
\par
    Slowness is not laziness. Slowness is the discipline of looking long enough to see the whole thing.\par
\par
    This book is a collection of small things I have learned by going slower than I was supposed to. There are ten movements. Each is short. Each is paired with a piece of art that is in the public domain \u8212? meaning it belongs to all of us, the way the sky and the alphabet belong to all of us.\par
\par
    You can read it cover to cover, but you do not have to. The pieces are short on purpose. Most of them are 250 to 600 words. I have learned that almost everything worth saying can be said on a single page; the rest is throat-clearing.\par
\par
    If you only have one minute today, read one aphorism. If you have ten, read one essay. If you have an evening, give it the evening. The book will not get up and leave.\par
\par
    \u8212? Non, written from a desk by the Yangtze, finished by the Chao Phraya, edited at six thousand metres above the Pacific.\par
\par
\cf3\i     [margin note] \u8961? on time The book is short on each page, long across the whole thing. Like a meal of many small dishes.\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [margin note] \u8961? on the art All ninety-three works are public domain. Print them. Frame them. Give them to your children.\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [margin note] \u8961? on the ten parts SLOW \u183? SEE \u183? LESS ALONE \u183? TIME \u183? MAKE FAIL \u183? PEOPLE \u183? HOME \u183? END\i0\cf0\par
\par
\par
\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 04 I-SLOW OPENER\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [section id: p1]\i0\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [announce; this is a chapter title \u8212? let it land]\i0\cf0\par
\par
    Slow.\par
\par
    A defence of the unhurried. The argument that the world is not, in fact, made for the fastest hand in the room.\par
\par
    Plate \u183? Katsushika Hokusai \u183? Fine Wind, Clear Morning \u183? c. 1830 \u183? Met / Wikimedia \u183? Public domain\par
\par
\par
\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 05 I-APH 1\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [slow, weighted; one beat per line]\i0\cf0\par
\par
    \u8961? Aphorism \u183? I.01\par
\par
\cf2\b     \u187? The world is not going to slow down. So you must.\b0\cf0\par
\par
    \u8212? Non, on a Tuesday in Shanghai\par
\par
\par
\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 06 I-WHY SLOW\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [conversational, like reading to a friend across a table]\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [kicker: \u8961? The first thing]\i0\cf0\par
    Speed is a cheap kind of beauty.\par
\par
    Speed is the most easily counterfeited virtue. A child can move quickly. A drone can move more quickly than a child. A piece of bad news travels around the world faster than the truth that corrects it.\par
\par
    What cannot be counterfeited is the long look. The decade-long study of one painter. The thirty years of waking up at five to write before work. The marriage that nobody photographed but everybody envied.\par
\par
    I lived in Shanghai during its fastest decade. I watched a city of bicycles become a city of e-scooters become a city of facial-recognition cameras. I am not nostalgic about the bicycles, exactly. I am nostalgic about the kind of attention a bicycle requires. You cannot ride a bicycle while looking at your phone. You cannot ride a bicycle and ignore the weather. The bicycle made you a participant in your own day.\par
\par
    Most of what we now call productivity is the opposite of that. It is the gradual outsourcing of attention to a faster machine, in exchange for the feeling that we are doing more. We are not doing more. We are doing the same things, badly, in front of a brighter screen.\par
\par
    Slow is not the opposite of busy. Slow is the opposite of distracted.\par
\par
    If you have ever watched an old craftsman work \u8212? a calligrapher, a tailor, a woman folding dumplings on a plastic stool \u8212? you have seen what slow really is. It is not delay. It is the absolute compression of attention into the present hand.\par
\par
    That is what this book is asking of you. Not less work. Better work. Not less life. More of the life you are already in.\par
\par
\cf3\i     [margin note] \u8961? overheard \u8220?He is not slow. He is doing it right the first time.\u8221? \u8212? my father, on a colleague who never missed a deadline.\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [margin note] \u8961? note The Italians have a word, sprezzatura , for the kind of effort that hides itself. The Japanese have shokunin \u8212? the craftsman whose slowness is the work.\i0\cf0\par
\par
\par
\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 07 I-PLATE PERSIMMONS\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [gallery-tour voice, gentle but assured]\i0\cf0\par
\par
    Plate: Six Persimmons\par
\cf3\i     [credit: Muqi (\u29287?\u-29633?) \u183? 13th c. \u183? Daitoku-ji, Kyoto \u183? Public domain]\i0\cf0\par
    Why we are looking at this:\par
    A monk made these six persimmons in ink in less time than it takes to drink tea, and they have been one of the most studied paintings in the world for eight hundred years. They are six brushstrokes, six greys, six different ways of being a fruit. The painter did not finish them quickly. He finished them once . There is a difference.\par
\par
\par
\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 08 I-ARDEN QUIET\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [punch lines \u8212? let the line break do the timing]\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [kicker: \u8961? I.03 \u183? A short observation]\i0\cf0\par
    \u171? Quiet rooms are full of information. \u187?\par
\par
    Hammersh\u248?i painted his own apartment in Copenhagen for thirty years. The wife. The doors. The sunlight on the floor. He found, in one address, what most painters look for by travelling. \u8961? Plate \u183? Vilhelm Hammersh\u248?i \u183? 1901 \u183? Statens Museum for Kunst.\par
\par
\par
\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 09 I-ON TRAINS\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [conversational, like reading to a friend across a table]\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [kicker: \u8961? A practical example]\i0\cf0\par
    In praise of the long train.\par
\par
    My favourite mode of transport is the overnight train. I know this is not the answer the airline industry would like me to give. I have given the answer many times anyway.\par
\par
    My first long train ride in China was Shanghai to Beijing in 2006. Ten and a half hours. I expected it to feel like waste. It felt like rest. Somewhere around hour four, I noticed I had stopped checking my watch. By hour seven, I had read more pages than in the previous month. By hour ten, I had become a person who could sit still.\par
\par
    A plane is a teleportation device that punishes you with bad food. A train is a small country with a window. The train acknowledges that you are alive in the time between two places. The plane pretends you are not.\par
\par
    I have taken many trains since. Shanghai\u8211?Guangzhou. Bangkok\u8211?Chiang Mai. Boston\u8211?DC. The pattern is always the same. The first hour, I am restless. The second hour, I begin to read. The third hour, the world out the window stops being a thing I am leaving and becomes a thing I am paying attention to.\par
\par
    A plane teleports you. A train returns you to yourself.\par
\par
    If you can afford the time, take the train. If you can't, sit at the gate for the same number of hours and read a real book without your phone. You will land a different person. The travel industry will not understand. You do not need them to.\par
\par
\cf3\i     [margin note] \u8961? data point I have written more pages on Chinese trains than at any desk I have ever owned.\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [margin note] \u8961? counter-argument A friend says: \u8220?If you love the train so much, why do you have a Star Alliance Gold card?\u8221? Fair. A long life has many compromises.\i0\cf0\par
\par
\par
\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 10 I-APH 2\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [slow, weighted; one beat per line]\i0\cf0\par
\par
    \u8961? Aphorism \u183? I.05\par
\par
\cf2\b     \u187? If you cannot tell whether you are working or wasting time, you are probably working.\b0\cf0\par
\par
    \u8212? A defence of the staring-out-the-window phase\par
\par
\par
\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 11 I-COMPARE SPEED\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [start with the title, then take time per figure]\i0\cf0\par
\par
    \u171? Two ways of moving through weather. \u187?\par
\par
    You are allowed to be either painting. The trick is to know which one you are looking at when you make decisions.\par
\par
\par
\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 12 I-ON TEA\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [same as essay \u8212? read the asides only after a 2s pause]\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [kicker: \u8961? A small ritual]\i0\cf0\par
    \u171? The tea is the lesson. Not the leaves. \u187?\par
\par
    Every morning my father drank tea from the same enamel cup. He boiled the water in the same dented kettle. He waited the same five minutes. He was an engineer; he was not a sentimental man. He never said the tea was a ritual. He drank it the same way every day for forty-five years and that, in the end, is what a ritual is.\par
\par
    I tried, in my twenties, to optimise my mornings. I read books about morning routines. I bought a kettle that beeped. I drank coffee out of a thermos in a taxi. I felt very modern, and I felt nothing.\par
\par
    Now I have an enamel cup. I do not always remember to use it. But the days I do are different from the days I don't.\par
\par
\cf3\i     [aside, slower] \u8961? a small dare For one week, drink one cup of something hot every morning, sitting down, with no screen. Notice what your mind does in the silence. Do not act on what it says. Just notice.\i0\cf0\par
\par
\par
\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 13 I-APH CLOSE\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [slow, weighted; one beat per line]\i0\cf0\par
\par
    \u8961? Closing \u183? I.09\par
\par
\cf2\b     \u187? You will never be more present than you decide to be.\b0\cf0\par
\par
    \u8212? end of Movement I \u183? turn the page slowly\par
