\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 14 II-SEE OPENER\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [section id: p2]\i0\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [announce; this is a chapter title \u8212? let it land]\i0\cf0\par
\par
    See.\par
\par
    Attention is the only luxury you can refuse to share with the algorithm. The hare is looking back at you.\par
\par
    Plate \u183? Albrecht D\u252?rer \u183? Young Hare \u183? 1502 \u183? Albertina, Vienna \u183? Public domain\par
\par
\par
\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 15 II-APH 1\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [slow, weighted; one beat per line]\i0\cf0\par
\par
    \u8961? Aphorism \u183? II.01\par
\par
\cf2\b     \u187? Looking is free. Seeing is expensive.\b0\cf0\par
\par
    \u8212? what every painting tries to say\par
\par
\par
\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 16 II-ATTENTION\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [conversational, like reading to a friend across a table]\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [kicker: \u8961? A confession]\i0\cf0\par
    I did not see my parents until I was thirty-two.\par
\par
    By see , I mean the verb a child does not know how to do, and an old man cannot stop doing. To see a person is to register that they are not, in fact, a function of your life. They have an interior the size of yours.\par
\par
    My father was an engineer at a state-owned company in Bangkok. He commuted ninety minutes each way. He never raised his voice. He read the newspaper at breakfast and he read it again at dinner. For most of my childhood, he was a quiet man-shaped object in the kitchen.\par
\par
    Then, one day, when I was thirty-two, he told me he had wanted to study astronomy.\par
\par
    This information rearranged my entire life. The man who never raised his voice had a sky inside him. The man with the tea flask had a different life he had not been allowed to live. He did not say this with regret. He said it with the same calm he said everything. But I had been living in his house for the first eighteen years of my life and I had not seen him.\par
\par
    Most of the people closest to you are wearing a costume. You have stopped noticing because you sewed it.\par
\par
    To see a person is to ask them a question whose answer you cannot guess. To see a painting is the same. To see a city is the same. The discipline is identical. It is the willingness to be wrong about what you thought was there.\par
\par
    I am still learning. I no longer assume my mother is only my mother. I no longer assume the cab driver is only a cab driver. I no longer assume Shanghai is the city I think it is. The world keeps showing me what was always there.\par
\par
\cf3\i     [margin note] \u8961? test Name three things your closest friend is afraid of. If you cannot, you have not been seeing them. You have been using them.\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [margin note] \u8961? a quote \u8220?We do not see things as they are. We see them as we are.\u8221? \u8212? attributed, by a hundred people, to Ana\u239?s Nin.\i0\cf0\par
\par
\par
\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 17 II-PLATE VERMEER\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [gallery-tour voice, gentle but assured]\i0\cf0\par
\par
    Plate: Woman Holding a Balance\par
\cf3\i     [credit: Johannes Vermeer \u183? c. 1664 \u183? National Gallery of Art \u183? Public domain]\i0\cf0\par
    Why we are looking at this:\par
    She is weighing nothing. Look closely: the pans are empty. The act of measuring is the subject. Vermeer is not painting a woman; he is painting attention \u8212? what it looks like to take a moment seriously before you act. Most of life is asking for this and getting answered too quickly.\par
\par
\par
\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 18 II-ARDEN PHONE\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [punch lines \u8212? let the line break do the timing]\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [kicker: \u8961? II.04 \u183? A working hypothesis]\i0\cf0\par
    \u171? The phone is not the problem. It is just the loudest symptom. \u187?\par
\par
    The instruments in D\u252?rer's Melencolia I \u8212? the compass, the hourglass, the bell, the magic square \u8212? are all instruments of attention. The figure is not depressed. She is paying close attention to something the painting does not show us. \u8961? Albrecht D\u252?rer \u183? 1514 \u183? the Met.\par
\par
