\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 29 III-SIX THINGS\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [same as essay \u8212? read the asides only after a 2s pause]\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [kicker: \u8961? Returning to the persimmons]\i0\cf0\par
    \u171? The argument for finishing things before you finish them. \u187?\par
\par
    I keep coming back to Muqi. Six persimmons, painted in maybe ten minutes, that have been studied for eight hundred years. The persimmons are not the same. One is darker. One is lighter. Two touch. They have a rhythm of differences, like a small choir, and the choir is the painting.\par
\par
    Muqi could have added a seventh. He could have added a leaf, a vase, a bird. He stopped. He stopped at the moment the painting became most itself. This is, in my experience, the hardest skill in any art: knowing when you are done.\par
\par
    Most people stop too late, because they are still trying to convince themselves it is good. The art of less is the art of stopping at the moment of recognition, before the moment of doubt.\par
\par
\cf3\i     [aside, slower] \u8961? a question What in your life would be better with one fewer of? Not zero. One fewer.\i0\cf0\par
