\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 39 V-AGING\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [conversational, like reading to a friend across a table]\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [kicker: \u8961? On aging well]\i0\cf0\par
    I want to age like a building by Louis Kahn.\par
\par
    Kahn said good architecture ages beautifully . He did not say it endures. He did not say it is fashionable. He said it gets better with weather, with use, with the small disasters of living. Concrete softens. Wood darkens. Stone keeps the marks of the people who have leaned on it.\par
\par
    I want to age that way. Not against time. Not despite it. With it. The way a temple roof sags slightly into its joinery and is more itself for the sag.\par
\par
    The opposite of this is the cosmetic life \u8212? the life that pretends nothing is happening. I have known people who, at sixty, look thirty-five, and have nothing to say. The fastest path to a small life is a refusal to take time on board.\par
\par
    Wrinkles are not damage. They are evidence.\par
\par
    I have a few wrinkles already, in the corners of my eyes, from squinting at trains and at students who were lying about their dissertations. I am not going to remove them. They are receipts. The face I am earning is the face I want to die in.\par
\par
    If I am lucky, I will become a slightly weathered version of the person I was at thirty \u8212? the same person, only more clearly. That is what an old building does. It does not become a new building. It becomes a more honest version of itself.\par
\par
\cf3\i     [margin note] \u8961? kahn \u8220?Even a brick wants to be something.\u8221? \u8212? Louis Kahn, in conversation with a brick.\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [margin note] \u8961? corollary You are also a brick. What do you want to be?\i0\cf0\par
\par
