\par
\cf3\i     [kicker: \u8961? Notes from a desk]\i0\cf0\par
    In praise of the floor planers.\par
\par
    Caillebotte painted three men on their knees, scraping the wood floor of a Paris apartment. The painting was rejected by the Salon. It was, the jury said, vulgar. It showed labour. It did not show ideals.\par
\par
    It is now one of my favourite paintings. The men are not heroes. They are not victims. They are working. The light is on their backs. They are, in their three different postures, one continuous act of attention. Caillebotte saw what most painters did not: that the room these men were preparing was, in fact, the painting.\par
\par
    I think about the floor planers on the days I do not want to work. There is a kind of work that is easy to romanticise \u8212? the writing of a great novel, the founding of a company, the design of a building. There is another kind of work that is harder to talk about: the daily work of preparing the surface on which the great thing might happen.\par
\par
    Most of life is the second kind.\par
\par
    Genius is a rumour. Habit is a receipt.\par
\par
    I have published papers, given talks, founded companies, built things people use. None of those are the work. The work was the morning. The work was sitting down at the desk again on the day after the bad one. The work was the floor planing. The visible thing \u8212? the talk, the paper, the launch \u8212? was a single floorboard in a long apartment.\par
\par
    If you are looking for a vocation, do not look for a calling. Look for a kind of work whose floor planing you can stand. That is the work.\par
\par
\cf3\i     [margin note] \u8961? a definition Vocation: the activity whose boring middle hour you can survive without resentment.\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [margin note] \u8961? counter If you only love the photographable parts of your work, you do not love your work. You love being seen working.\i0\cf0\par
\par
