\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 52 VII-TUNNEL\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [conversational, like reading to a friend across a table]\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [kicker: \u8961? A confession in two parts]\i0\cf0\par
    I wish I had never done a PhD. \u8212? and I would do it again.\par
\par
    Six years into a PhD I had begun to suspect I should not have started, the graduate school sent me a survey. The first question was: Would you do this again? My finger hovered over Yes . Of course I would. I had spent six years preparing the answer.\par
\par
    Then I did not click. I sat in front of the screen for a long time. The question, I realised, was not asking what I would do; it was asking what the six years had taught me. And what the six years had taught me was that I had walked through a long, mostly unlit tunnel, on the assumption that there was a room at the end. There was no room. There was a door, and on the other side of the door was a different version of me \u8212? older, slower, more honest, less impressed.\par
\par
    I would not do the PhD again. And I would do the tunnel again. The tunnel was not the PhD. The tunnel was the slow, private dismantling of a younger man's certainty. That dismantling had to happen somewhere. It happened to happen there.\par
\par
    Failure is not the opposite of success. Failure is the slower form of teaching.\par
\par
    I have been thrown under buses by people I trusted. I have had projects refuse to ship, books refuse to finish, students refuse to learn from a teacher who had something to teach. I have spent more nights than I would like staring at a ceiling, drafting in my head the sentence that would have ended the argument, that I never said.\par
\par
    None of these were failures. They were tunnels. The mistake, every time, was thinking the tunnel was the destination \u8212? and getting angry at the dark.\par
\par
    If you are in a tunnel right now, I cannot tell you how long it is. Nobody can. But I can tell you that the dark is doing something to you that the daylight cannot do. Hold on. Walk slowly. Pay attention to the texture of the walls. The room you walk out into is the room you would not otherwise have been able to see.\par
\par
\cf3\i     [margin note] \u8961? a quote \u8220?The wound is the place where the light enters you.\u8221? \u8212? Rumi.\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [margin note] \u8961? also I once read that Beckett's editor returned a manuscript with the note fail again, fail better . The line was, of course, Beckett's own. He was its first reader.\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [margin note] \u8961? test If you cannot describe what your last failure taught you in one sentence, the lesson is not over.\i0\cf0\par
\par
\par
