\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 60 VIII-ON FATHER\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [same as essay \u8212? read the asides only after a 2s pause]\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [kicker: \u8961? The man who never socialised]\i0\cf0\par
    \u171? I learned everything I know about people from a man who avoided them. \u187?\par
\par
    My father was an introvert in a culture that does not have a word for it. He had two close friends, both engineers. He saw them once a month. He spent the rest of his time with my mother, with us, and with himself. He was not unhappy. He was, in fact, the calmest happy man I have known.\par
\par
    What he taught me about people was, mostly, this: the people you love are the people whose company does not require a performance. Everyone else is an event. Events are fine. They are not the life.\par
\par
    He died slowly, over a year. I sat with him on more afternoons than I would have, in a faster life. We did not say much. He was tired. I read the newspaper to him, the way he had read it to himself for forty years. It was the closest I have been to anyone, and we said almost nothing.\par
\par
\cf3\i     [aside, slower] \u8961? note If you can sit in silence with someone for an hour and feel met, you are home.\i0\cf0\par
\par
