\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 64 IX-THREE CITIES\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [conversational, like reading to a friend across a table]\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [kicker: \u8961? Three cities, in chronological order]\i0\cf0\par
    Bangkok, Boston, Shanghai.\par
\par
    Bangkok taught me that the world is a market. Boston taught me that the world is a library. Shanghai taught me that the world is, mostly, an unfinished construction site, and that this is not a complaint.\par
\par
    I was born in Bangkok. I went to school there in a uniform that did not breathe. I walked, every morning, past a noodle stall whose owner I now realise was teaching me what it meant to do the same job, well, for forty years. He died last year. I did not go back for the funeral. I am sorry about this in the part of myself that is still Thai.\par
\par
    Boston was my first foreign weather. I arrived in September and was unprepared for snow. I bought a coat that was too thin and walked to MIT in it for a year before I admitted it. Boston was where I first learned to be alone in a city. The library at MIT is open most of the night. I learned to live there. The radiators clicked. The students did not look up. I read Kahn, and Kant, and Bachelard. I came home each night through the bridge over the Charles. I was twenty-three. I think I was mostly happy.\par
\par
    Shanghai was the third city, and the longest. Ten years. Two studios. One marriage, ending. One book, beginning. I learned, in Shanghai, that a city can teach you to be both bigger and smaller \u8212? bigger because the city is large, smaller because, in a city of twenty-six million, no single person is the protagonist. The city's lesson is humility. The city's other lesson is delight. The two are connected.\par
\par
    Home is not where you were born. Home is where you have agreed to be vulnerable.\par
\par
    I now live, when I can, in all three. I keep a desk in each. The desks are different sizes. The chairs are different heights. The view out the window is different. The work I do is the same. This is the trick I have learned: home is not a place. Home is a posture. You can sit that posture down anywhere.\par
\par
\cf3\i     [margin note] \u8961? a question If you had three desks anywhere in the world, where would they be? Trust the second answer. The first is the one your parents trained you to give.\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [margin note] \u8961? Bachelard \u8220?The house allows one to dream in peace.\u8221? \u8212? Gaston Bachelard, The Poetics of Space .\i0\cf0\par
\par
