\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 71 X-ENOUGH\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [conversational, like reading to a friend across a table]\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [kicker: \u8961? Notes for the last page]\i0\cf0\par
    The word I am trying to learn is enough.\par
\par
    Enough is a hard word in any language I speak. In English it sounds like a defeat. In Thai it sounds like resignation. In Mandarin it sounds like an instruction to a child. None of these is what the word actually means.\par
\par
    Enough is the word that means: I have what I need to live well today. The day will end. The work will not be finished. That is fine. The work is not the point. The day is the point.\par
\par
    I have spent most of my life chasing more. More degrees. More projects. More cities. More languages. More respect. More publications. There is nothing wrong with more. More is the engine. But more is not the destination. Enough is the destination.\par
\par
    More is what you do. Enough is what you become.\par
\par
    If I am lucky, I will reach the end of my life having said the word enough out loud, to myself, on most days. Enough food. Enough work. Enough friends. Enough hours. Enough.\par
\par
    The plum blossoms in K\u333?rin's screen are not many. There are not few, either. They are exactly enough to make the painting a painting. I do not know how K\u333?rin knew. I think he knew because he had stopped trying to add.\par
\par
    I am still learning. Most days I add. On the days I subtract, I notice my breathing. I notice the room. I notice you, if you are with me. I notice that the rest of my life, however long, is going to be made out of these noticings.\par
\par
    That is, in the end, why I wrote this book. Not to teach you anything. To remind myself, on the days I forget.\par
\par
\cf3\i     [margin note] \u8961? a vow To say the word enough at least once, every day, out loud, until I mean it.\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [margin note] \u8961? also K\u333?rin painted these plums on a folding screen meant to be opened in a single room. Not for a museum. Not for posterity. For a friend's tea ceremony. The right scale, for the right room.\i0\cf0\par
\par
\par
\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 72 X-PLATE WANDERER\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [gallery-tour voice, gentle but assured]\i0\cf0\par
\par
    Plate: Wanderer above the Sea of Fog\par
\cf3\i     [credit: Caspar David Friedrich \u183? c. 1818 \u183? Hamburger Kunsthalle \u183? Public domain]\i0\cf0\par
    Why we are looking at this:\par
    The most famous painting of a man with his back turned. He is alone. The fog is the future. He has climbed for hours to look at it. He does not know what is below the fog. Neither do you. Neither do I. The painting is not a tragedy. The painting is a posture. He is still standing. So are we. That is most of the assignment.\par
\par
\par
\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 73 X-APH 2\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [slow, weighted; one beat per line]\i0\cf0\par
\par
    \u8961? Aphorism \u183? X.05\par
\par
\cf2\b     \u187? The thing you would write on your last day is the thing you should be writing now.\b0\cf0\par
\par
    \u8212? and you have more days than you think\par
\par
\par
\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 74 X-LAST LESSON\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [same as essay \u8212? read the asides only after a 2s pause]\i0\cf0\par
\par
\cf3\i     [kicker: \u8961? The last lesson]\i0\cf0\par
    \u171? What you have read is what I have so far figured out. \u187?\par
\par
    I am, by middle age, in possession of a small number of facts. They are the facts I would tell my younger self over a long dinner if I could. They will not change his life. They will, possibly, save him a year or two of unnecessary speed.\par
\par
    You will not finish what you started. You will not see all of the people you love before they are gone. You will not be famous in the way a younger you wanted to be. You will not be saved by any of the things you currently expect to save you.\par
\par
    And: there will be more long afternoons than you imagine. There will be a kind of slow, late happiness that does not announce itself. There will be a particular smell in a particular kitchen, in a particular city, that returns you to yourself in a single breath. There will be friends who turn out to be the kind you can sit with in silence. That is, in the end, plenty.\par
\par
    If this book has done its job, you have already paused once or twice in the reading. That is the book. The text was a pretext. The pause was the lesson.\par
\par
\cf3\i     [aside, slower] \u8961? on closing Close this book gently. Put it down. Look out a window. That part is the assignment.\i0\cf0\par
\par
\par
\par\par\cf2\b\f2\fs32 \u9619?\u9619?\u9619? 75 X-FINAL\b0\f0\fs28\cf0\par
\cf3\i     [slow, weighted; one beat per line]\i0\cf0\par
\par
    \u8961? Final aphorism \u183? X.09\par
\par
\cf2\b     \u187? Slow down. The world has been waiting for you to notice it.\b0\cf0\par
\par
    \u8212? end of book \u183? thank you for staying\par
\par
